Note:
C Emitter - Buffered output for C code generation

This file provides buffered output functionality for C code generation.
All buffer management, character/string emission, and indentation logic
is delegated to the shared byte-buffer foundation in emitter_common.runa.
The wrappers below preserve the C-emitter public API so existing callers
(hir_to_c.runa) continue to use the same names.

Conventions:
- Dynamic buffer growth (amortized O(1) appends) via emitter_common
- C uses 4-space indentation for blocks and statements
- Null-terminated output strings (get_output returns a fresh copy)
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/emitter_common.runa" as EmitterCommon

Note: ============================================================================
Note: C Emitter Structure
Note: ============================================================================
Note: CEmitter is the same 24-byte header layout used by emitter_common's raw
Note: API (buffer at offset 0, capacity at 8, length at 16). The fields are
Note: declared here for type-name clarity in C-specific code; the storage is
Note: managed entirely by emitter_common.
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Typed view of the shared 24-byte emitter header for C-backend code. Keeps
C-specific call sites readable while delegating all storage management
to emitter_common.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three Integer fields at offsets 0, 8, 16 - byte-compatible with the
emitter_common raw header layout. Do not add fields without updating
EMITTER_HEADER_SIZE.
@End Implementation

Type called "CEmitter":
    buffer as Integer
    capacity as Integer
    length as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Emitter Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Named constructor so call sites use the C-specific spelling instead of
referring to the shared raw helper directly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_create which allocates a 24-byte header and an
initial-capacity byte buffer. Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_c_emitter" returns Integer:
    Note: Create C emitter via emitter_common raw header allocation.
    Return proc emitter_raw_create from EmitterCommon
End Process

@Reasoning:
Paired destructor for create_c_emitter. Frees buffer and header.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_destroy. Null emitter is a safe no-op returning 1.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Caller must drop the emitter pointer after this call.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "destroy_c_emitter" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy C emitter and free buffer via emitter_common.
    Return proc emitter_raw_destroy from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Buffer Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public capacity-reservation hook for callers that know they will emit a
large chunk and want to avoid intermediate buffer doublings.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_ensure_capacity which doubles capacity until the
request fits.
@End Implementation

Process called "ensure_capacity" takes emitter as Integer, needed as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Geometric growth handled by emitter_common.
    Return proc emitter_raw_ensure_capacity from EmitterCommon with emitter, needed
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Output Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single-byte append for C punctuation (braces, semicolons, commas).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_emit_byte.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_char" takes emitter as Integer, char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit single character byte.
    Return proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Append a null-terminated string. The most-used emitter helper for C
keywords, identifiers, types, and operators.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_emit_string which measures length once and bulk
copies. Null/empty strings are no-ops.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_string" takes emitter as Integer, str as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit null-terminated string.
    Return proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter, str
End Process

@Reasoning:
Combined "emit string then newline" used at the end of each statement and
directive for clean line-oriented output.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits the string then a single LF (byte 10).
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_line" takes emitter as Integer, str as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit string followed by newline byte.
    proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter, str
    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 10
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Named newline helper so the line terminator can be retuned globally.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits a single LF (byte 10).
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_newline" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit newline byte.
    Return proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 10
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single space helper - used between tokens in expressions and parameter
lists.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits a single SP (byte 32).
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_space" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit single space byte.
    Return proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 32
End Process

@Reasoning:
C convention is 4 spaces per indentation level. Centralised here so the
width can be changed in one place.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops level * 4 times emitting space byte (32).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(level * 4). For deep nesting the loop is still negligible compared to
the surrounding emit string costs.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "emit_indent" takes emitter as Integer, level as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit indentation as 4 space bytes per nesting level. C convention.
    Let total_spaces be level multiplied by 4
    Let count be 0
    While count is less than total_spaces:
        proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 32
        Set count to count plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Output Retrieval
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Snapshot the buffer into a heap-allocated null-terminated copy. Called
once at end-of-translation; the caller owns the returned pointer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_get_output which allocates length+1 bytes, copies
the buffer, NUL-terminates, and returns the new pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_output" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return a freshly allocated null-terminated copy of the emitted bytes.
    Return proc emitter_raw_get_output from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Expose current write position for back-patching and section-size
computation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_length which reads the length field at offset 16.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_length" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return the current number of bytes written to the buffer.
    Return proc emitter_raw_length from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reuse the buffer for a subsequent translation without reallocating.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_reset which zeroes the length field; capacity
unchanged.
@End Implementation

Process called "reset" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Reset emitter to empty state, retaining the allocated buffer.
    Return proc emitter_raw_reset from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process
